    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-01-11T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-01-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="612"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d612">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151/981: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-01-11T12:00:00+07:00"
                            >January 11, 1944—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received January 11—8:06
                        a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>58. To Secretary of Treasury from Adler, re your 15, January 3.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>I fully agree with your (2). Appropriate Chinese institution for
                        consultation is Commission for Control of Foreign Exchange Assets to which
                        Chinese staff board is being transferred. It is most unlikely that any
                        Chinese Government body consulted in connection with type of transaction
                        referred to in your (3) would take a stiff attitude. Presumably unless
                        satisfactory arrangement is worked out with Chinese authorities for covering
                        U. S. Government agencies’ <hi rend="italic">fapi</hi> requirements, more
                        liberal licensing policy referred to in your (2) would also be applied to U.
                        S. Government agencies’ transactions. As you know, U. S. Government civilian
                        agencies in China acting in accordance with instructions from Washington
                        have been selling U. S. currency in black market for more than a month now
                        while American soldiers have been financing their personal expenditures by
                        the same means for the past 2 years.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Re your 1690, November 24.<note n="25" xml:id="d612fn25">
                            <ref target="frus1943China#pg_474">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1943, China, p.
                            474</ref>.</note> British have not yet given 30 days’ notice of
                        termination required under 1941 Sino-British agreement. Shall I submit my
                        resignation as of January 31?</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Your 658, May 24<note n="26" xml:id="d612fn26">
                            <ref target="frus1943China#pg_418">
                                <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 418</ref>.</note> and my TF–138,
                        July 15.<note n="27" xml:id="d612fn27">See telegram No. 1200, July 16, 1943,
                            1 p.m., from the Chargé in China, <ref target="frus1943China#pg_427">
                                <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, p. 427</ref>.</note> Ministry of
                        Finance has recently asked me for your reaction to Kung’s alternative plan.
                        [Adler.]</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
